Title : Epitome Astronomiae Copernicanae
Text : {{italic title}}
[[File:Kepler-Bruno.jpg|thumb|upright=1.3|Kepler's Figure 'M' from the ''Epitome'', showing the world as belonging to just one of any number of similar stars]]
[[File:Epitome astronomiae copernicanae.tif|thumb|''Epitome astronomiae copernicanae'' (1618)]]
The '''''Epitome Astronomiae Copernicanae''''' was an astronomy book on the [[heliocentric system]] published by [[Johannes Kepler]] in the period 1617 to 1621. The first volume (books I–III) was printed in 1617, the second (book IV) in 1620, and the third (books V–VII) in 1621.

==Content==
The book contained in particular the first version in print of his [[third law of planetary motion]]. The work was intended as a textbook, and the first part was written by 1615.<ref>{{cite book|author=Max Caspar|title=Kepler|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=cYQUAwAAQBAJ&pg=PA239|date=10 October 2012|publisher=[[Courier Dover Publications]]|isbn=978-0-486-15175-5|page=239}}</ref> Divided into seven books, the ''Epitome'' covers much of Kepler's earlier thinking, as well as his later positions on physics, metaphysics and archetypes.<ref name="Martens">{{cite book|author=Rhonda Martens|title=Kepler's Philosophy and the New Astronomy|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=8ATfXOItxNQC&pg=PA142|date=29 October 2000|publisher=[[Princeton University Press]]|isbn=0-691-05069-4|page=142}}</ref> In Book IV he supported the [[Copernican cosmology]].<ref>{{cite book|author1=[[Roy Porter]]|author2=Katharine Park|author3=Lorraine Daston|title=The Cambridge History of Science: Volume 3, Early Modern Science|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=2kvjAp92zcYC&pg=PA41|date=3 July 2006|publisher=[[Cambridge University Press]]|isbn=978-0-521-57244-6|page=41}}</ref> Book V provided mathematics underpinning Kepler's views.<ref name="Martens"/> Kepler wrote and published this work in parallel with his ''[[Harmonices Mundi]]'' (1619), the last Books V to VII appearing in 1621.<ref>{{cite book|author=J. R. Mulryne|title=Europa Triumphans: Court and Civic Festivals in Early Modern Europe|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Y-eW-RUKAicC&pg=PA12|date=1 January 2004|publisher=[[Ashgate Publishing, Ltd.]]|isbn=978-0-7546-3873-5|page=12}}</ref>

The term "[[inertia]]" was first introduced in the ''Epitome''.<ref>Lawrence Nolan (ed.), ''The Cambridge Descartes Lexicon'', Cambridge University Press, 2016, "Inertia."</ref>

The first volume was put on the Index of Prohibited Books on 28th of February 1619.<ref> Maurice Finocchiario, Retrying Galileo, 1633-1992, Chapter 1, page 20</ref>

==Editions==
* 1635 reprint: [https://books.google.gr/books?id=KUE1AAAAcAAJ&vq=inertia&hl=el&source=gbs_navlinks_s&redir_esc=y ''Epitome Astronomiae Copernicanae''], Vols. 1–3, Schönwetterus.

==Translations==
* 1939: ''Epitome of Copernican astronomy. Books IV and V, The organization of the world and the doctrine ...''; trans. by Charles Glenn Wallis. Annapolis: St John's Bookstore.
* 1955:   Reissued with Ptolemy's Almagest. Chicago: Encyclopædia Britannica (1955).
* 1995: ''Epitome of Copernican astronomy; & Harmonies of the world''; translated by Charles Glenn Wallis. Amherst: Prometheus Books.

